6. It is known that the squares of positive integers with two digits are: $16,25,36,49,64,81$.

Notice that, starting from the given numbers, there is at most one two-digit square, so after the first two-digit number is chosen, the remaining part of the desired number is uniquely determined. Since there are no two-digit square numbers starting with 5 or 9, the desired number cannot start with 25 or 49.
From 16, we get 164,1649;
From 36, we get 364,3649;
From 64, we get 649;
From 81, we get $816,8164,81649$.
Therefore, the numbers that satisfy the condition are
$$
164,1649,364,3649,649,816,8164,81649 .
$$

