soln_description:
Solution. Let's use the substitution $u=1-\cos x$, from which $d u=$ $=\sin x d x$. Then we will find the new limits of integration; substituting into the equation $u=1-\cos x$ the values $x_{1}=\pi / 2$ and $x_{2}=\pi$, we will respectively obtain $u_{1}=1-\cos (\pi / 2)=1$ and $u_{2}=1-\cos \pi=2$. The solution is written as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \int_{\pi / 2}^{\pi} \frac{2 \sin x d x}{(1-\cos x)^{2}}=\left|\begin{array}{l}
u=1-\cos x, u_{1}=1-\cos (\pi / 2)=1, \\
d u=\sin x d x ; u_{2}=1-\cos \pi=2
\end{array}\right|=2 \int_{u}^{u_{2}} \frac{d u}{u^{2}}=2 \int_{1}^{2} u^{-2} d u= \\
& =-\left.2 u^{-1}\right|_{1} ^{2}=-1+2=1
\end{aligned}
$$

From $a^{2}+b^{2}=c^{2}$ with $a ; b ; c \in N$ it follows that

$$
\begin{array}{cc}
a^{2}+b^{2}-c^{2}=0 & ; \quad(a+b)^{2}-c^{2}=2 a b \\
(a+b-c)(a+b+c)=2 a b & ; \quad \frac{(a+b-c) c}{2}=\frac{a b c}{a+b+c}
\end{array}
$$

(due to $a+b+c \neq 0$ and $\frac{c}{2} \neq 0$). The term $\frac{a b c}{a+b+c}$ is an integer if and only if the term $(a+b-c) c$ is an even number. Now, $a+b-c$ is always an even number. If $c$ is even, then $c^{2}$ and consequently $a^{2}+b^{2}$ are even, so $a$ and $b$ are either both even or both odd; if, on the other hand, $c$ is odd, then $c^{2}$ and consequently one of the two numbers $a$ and $b$ is odd, making $a+b$ odd. In either case, $(a+b-c) c$ is an even number, and thus

$$
\frac{(a+b-c) c}{2}=\frac{a b c}{a+b+c}
$$

is an integer.

